Patch summary:
Add the Cuttlefish device-side foundation for LineageOS Desktop products. This
includes Ika-specific desktop device entries, tablet-compatible feature declarations,
batteryless VM health behavior, graphics/property plumbing, and vendor overlay
placement needed by the desktop images.

The goal is to make the guest identify like a tablet-compatible desktop virtual
machine rather than a phone or Play-visible PC. That means removing mobile-only
assumptions where the host is responsible for the hardware experience, while
preserving the Cuttlefish pieces still needed for boot, graphics, and packaging.
Host-side AVB key lookup is also pointed at the ROM/product bundle first, so
the ROM owns its signing keys and empty host placeholders cannot shadow them.
The patch also carries the generated Soong serializer expected by the pinned
Cuttlefish snapshot, keeping bootstrap verification reproducible. OTA vendor
post-install metadata follows the board filesystem type so update_engine mounts
ext4 and EROFS vendor images with the format they were actually built with.
The Cuttlefish NPU APEX is disabled for this tree because the pinned Cuttlefish
snapshot is ahead of the platform NPU Rust interface variants available here.
The Bluetooth service is kept on the offload modules available in this platform
tree by omitting the newer A2DP offload crate.
Ika desktop products also disable the newer Bluetooth LPP service instance when
this platform tree does not provide its socket service binary.
Desktop SELinux extensions cover expected graphics debug-property reads and
host-driven shell helpers so normal boot, scrcpy, and resize/provisioning flows
do not leave avoidable enforcing-mode denials behind.
The ARM64 desktop target is pinned to ARMv8.2-A as its minimum device ISA.
ARM64 hosts are allowed to satisfy accelerated GPU mode requirements because
Ika explicitly carries and tests the ARM64 host graphics stack.
Userdata stays ext4 and sparse/thin-provisioned, with the default size raised
to 61 GiB.
snd-aloop is excluded from the boot ramdisks on both architectures so
virtio-snd enumerates as ALSA card 0: the generic AIDL audio HAL plays to
card 0/device 0 by default, and a first-stage-loaded loopback card would
silently swallow the guest audio meant for the host virtio-snd server.
The primary audio policy also omits Cuttlefish's VTS-only MMAP ports. Modern
AIDL audio HALs derive MMAP availability from those routes and ignore the
legacy aaudio.mmap_policy properties, so removing the routes keeps games on
the functional legacy mixer that feeds virtio-snd.
ADB host exposure is loopback-only while user builds keep guest TCP ADB
available without interactive key authorization.

